reviews.text: An iconic global centre of the world that has inspired the world with its brilliant architecture, movies, and art. Also known as the Big Apple, New York is well-known for its magnificent skyscrapers, Broadway shows and beautiful landmarks, making it the perfect destination for travellers from all over the world. From the flashy neon lights and the hustle and bustle of Times Square to the skyscrapers of Wall Street and the verdant ways of Central Park, New York City never ceases to amaze with its energy and vibrancy. World-class exhibition halls like MoMA and exceptional world heritage sites like the Statue of Liberty are simply captivating. Broadway shows, ethnic enclaves and shops, memorable lanes of stately brownstones, in vogue bars and diners all add to the urban buzz. This modern city is home to millions of immigrants and is cosmopolitan in a way no other city can be.

Also known as the Big Apple, New York is well-known for its magnificent skyscrapers, Broadway shows and beautiful landmarks, making it the perfect destination for travellers from all over the world. This modern city is home to millions of immigrants and is cosmopolitan in a way no other city can be.

Seeing it from the outside is beautiful but after going up into it, the views are perhaps even more beautiful than the building itself. Not the most prominent building in New York but certainly one of the most spectacular. Its Art Deco style is very similar to that of the Empire State Building, with a rectangular lower half that narrows into a cone, ending with a spire at the top.

The most beautiful building in NYC. It's pure Artdeco. With a timeless architecture it's roof it's beautiful at night and even during the day. It's mythical. You can enter inside the lobby and observe the walls made of marble and metal.
There is not and observatory. It's a shame! I would love to go up and see the perspective from there.

My eye doctor has his office in this building.  I must say I have never been able to go all the way to the top, but the view must be breathtaking, with Grand Central station close by and all the other buildings close by, including the new skyscraper on Vanderbilt avenue. The entrance on 42nd street is usually clean, even though it's always busy, with tourists, the subway entrance and people who work in the building. But don't get discouraged.

It has some of the largest video boards I have ever seen.  They are so clear and you can see them from blocks away.  There are many large national chains there. The street performers are very entertaining and like to have crowd participation.  You will see people from all walks of life and many countries.  It is a great place to people watch

Times Square is just magical! This place must be in your bucket list❤️ Is beautiful, breathtaking and so different. It has so many places to visit. Some many restaurant options, spots to take amazing pictures, shopping for everyone. You will definitely fall in love with Times Square, just like I did💕

I just had a really great time. The food was awesome. There was something to see all the time, something was always going on.  Very interesting people from all aspects of life. People were in costumes looking good and doing their own thing.  I just loved it.

Excellent Mind blowing place. full of Skyscraper building all around. one can spend whole day time here without being bored.
Night at Time square is awesome.Hotels, food and shopping outlets & other shop all around can be seen. 
lightning and shops will cheers you during night and evening time. never sleep city of country USA
many food restaurants are there, people from all around the world can be seen here. New York has its own charm. its on 7th Avenue. 
many subways are there for commute. Tourist buses run time to time and can be available on spot or online. NJ Transits are available connecting New Jersey. I loved enjoying coming from Ramsay New jersey to Penn Station New York. Overall amazing place i visited in Sep 2010.

The iconic Time Square. I have always wanted to go and I achieved my goal to come. There’s so many different apps and restaurants to go to. So many interesting people. It is filled with life. Truly shows that New York is the city that never sleeps.

When I was in New York for the first time in 2016 we passed through the church with friends but they didn't want to go inside. For four years I couldn't erase it from my mind and I regretted for not visiting it. I don't even know why. I didn't know anything about the church before. Never heard anything of it but it seems important in some ways to me because it was the first thing I visited after I returned to New York. That never happened to me before. I spent about an hour there before they closed and I was amazed how hard work and love and dedication they put into it. It’s art. And it’s so quiet and peaceful compared to crazy Manhattan. It makes you feel safe, peaceful, honored. I am not very religious or anything but this was a special moment. So I highly recommend visiting it and try to appreciate your life. I don’t think you’ll be sorry. It’s free, photos are allowed and it’s one of the best things ever.

Absolutely amazing! Be prepared for large crowds and lines, but lines move relatively fast. It is definitely worth the wait whether you are religious or not it is something to see. Please be respectful when going it is a cathedral and they do services there. People come to pay their respects to those passed at the beautiful statues through out the church as well as come to go to the services and pray.

Majestic icon in NYC. We visited on a Saturday and were pleased to see people understanding the reverence of this cathedral. (So many time tourists disregard the fact it is a church!). Beautifully ornate and they have several areas for lighting candles for prayer intentions. A gift shop is located just down 51st street. If you’re a Catholic, this should be a must-see.

One of the Great Historic Places in the city you should not miss. 
Try to research and get inside while they perform service. Usually its pretty crowded, so come earlier, and enjoy the majesty and great architecture.
The St. Patrick's Cathedral is aesthetically pleasing place and located in the heart of the city on Fifth Ave right across Rockefeller Center, which is another great tourist attraction place.

A beautiful piece of history.  A must-visit landmark for residents and tourists alike. Friendly and welcoming staff, breath-taking works of art, sculptures, stained glass and environment. It doesn't matter whether you're stopping by for a service, to pray, or to just marvel in the astonishing architecture and craftsmanship.  St. Patrick's Cathedral is a must-see stop for anyone!

Nice and tidy park. You can enjoy walking around or bench-sitting here. Relaxation. From here you can also take a ferry to the Statue of Liberty. Otherwise, you have a beautiful view on it from park. There are many outdoor shows in the park. As well as some monuments honoring soldiers and explorers.

I feel like this area should be updated.  As a tourist, it felt very run down and could use some love.  If it is the official place to view the statue, it didn't feel like it.  The monuments were impressive.

Underrated and amazing spot in New York City. I've been to New York a million times as my family is from Brooklyn but I've never been to this park. It's beautiful, spacious, and kept clean. Nearby are pieces of the Berlin Wall, the raging bull statute, a viewpoint for the Statue of Liberty, and several beautifully made memorials for the Armed Forces. I highly recommend walking about this entire area but definitely make sure to wander through Battery Park. Castle Clinton, the immigrants statue, and several other sites are a must see.

Beautiful park at the bottom tip of the island.. it's filled with tourists gawking at statue of liberty during the day and it's quietly peaceful and beautiful at night with all the vintage-style street lights overlooking the brightly lit statue of liberty. Definitely worth a visit for tourists and local alike.

I love this place.It's so beautiful if you see it at sunset. Battery Park is one of the most unforgettable places that I've been in NYC. I will definitely come back when I have a chance to go NYC again. It's a must go!!👍👍😭❤

Such a great public park. Park is a good field for sport, there is a long-running road around the whole park. 
Park consist ancient architecture, and very old trees 🌲, some of them has more than 200 years. I think this park has more potential than Central Park in Manhattan but unfortunately is has definitely about 10times less financial supports the other mentioned.Nevertheless it’s great  place to visit.

What a perfect place to experience Brooklyn and just relax, walk, run or take a stroll. A very nice path, vegetation, and occasional horses. Parking is limited but not impossible. We came there for the Gaza 5K from Unrwa USA and the crew were helpful and the weather was amazing. We will be back soon.

I'm born and raised in Brooklyn and i always find myself at Prospect Park and Grand Army Library. It's a great spot if you love digs. Tons of dog owners in this area. It's definitely come a long way since I was a kid as far as safety.

What’s not to love about green space in the middle of the city. Love going here to get away from the hustle and bustle. Great to see all the improvements they have made over the years. The coffee shop by the skating rink has surprisingly good food. My father in law said how he had the best vegan burger in years there.
Great place for biking, fishing, running. Nice for picnics. Also a wedding destination. Big lake for different activities. There is a water dog park. Historic park. Near great restaurants as well

Probably the largest park in Brooklyn; it has everything with basketball courts on one pier and a turf soccer field on another. You can even access it from two ferry stops. A great place to just chill by the water with fantastic, up-close views of lower Manhattan! Time-Out Market is so close on the North side of the park with great food options.

Well, there's no shortage of words to describe this absolute beast of a monument. Contrary to the pictures everyone posts from up on it, I'm opting to post pictures from night below and around it. Be it romantic, memorable, jaw dropping, be it anything Brooklyn bridge delivers. I'll let the professionals and the photogenics post pictures from up top, while I'll give those who prefer aesthetics a view of what they could click. Banger of a place and if you're up for it, you could even dip your feet or hands in the chilling waters at night. This is the place to be at!

Amazing view of the Manhattan, especially at nights! The park is open till 9/10 pm and has a bunch of sport activities that one can engage. It's the perfect spot for any occasion, especially on warm nights. If you come by car, just know that you will have to pay $2 for every hour spent at the designated parking area. It only accepts cards, no cash. This also has a great view of both Brooklyn and Manhattan bridge and if you walk a bit further, there are picnic tables as well as benches along the park.

Beautiful park worth exploring. It's great to see the iconic bridge up close. I wish we had time to walk/jog across but the drive is beautiful too. You can feel the energy change as you cross into Manhattan. The park itself is wide open offering the best skyline views imaginable. This park a selfie backdrop moment waiting to happen! There's also a museum and lots of restaurants and shops nearby.

Love this park. Almost always over crowded and hectic but still nice to hangout with the kids, take a walk through, and enjoy the scenery. Wish the few stops with food and drinks weren't extremely expensive but that's gentrified Dumbo for you. Still would recommend.

Great place.  Time passes unnoticed there.  All celebrities are just as alive.  Very interesting and we really liked it.  It’s good to come there with the whole family.  You will not regret the money spent.  A lot of fun and lots of beautiful celebrity photos. Thank you

First time and it’s worth the money and experience. I loved it! I wished it wasn’t over crowded though It was a weekend. I’m sad that I missed a floor and a few sections because it was big. Saw many of my favourites actors and actresses. Definitely worth the wait in the line which is about 10 minutes not even.

An absolutely AMAZING experience!! This place was SO cool, they have everyone from actors, presidents, writers, superheros, the list goes on and on. All of the wax figures are SO well done. Some of them are so good that they seem real. I would be lying if I said I didn't mistake a wax figure for a real person during my tour.

Absolutely loved this experience!!! The Groupon voucher helped with the price also. Definitely a place to visit while you are in New York Times Square. Me and my fiance spent 3 hours exploring and taking pictures and interacting with the wax figures. So many different exhibits. Would recommend to anyone visiting Times Square.

Very nice experience. Lots of fun. You can take pictures with wax figures (leaders, singers, movie stars) and these will be a beautiful memory. Some of the performances are perfect, others a little smaller. Good markings and great information regarding figures. Find out something new. Very interesting. Visiting somewhere between two and three hours.

I couldn't ask for more! This Playroom was stunning for me and for my kids. They love to come back again. I am deeply impressed by how they handled their many customers politely with no hassles at all. Such a wonderful day spent at this fantastic place. It was a nice experience for me for the first time. Terrific!

Cashiers seemed occupied with each others social lives. Store was pretty neat. Had a greater at the base of the elevator give us the rundown on the 3 floors. Everything was fully stocked and appealing.
I got a chance to get a pound of M&Ms from their M&M wall. There are all sorts of flavors. I got some cheesecake, peanut butter, peanut filled, coffee, toffee, and dark chocolate. Although $7.99 a half pound, it was cool to see all those flavors. I think I'd only go back for souvenirs for family members.

Here is really a huge range of M&M products. The store has three floors. There is a wall with many pillars filled with M&M candies of all colors. Really fantastic. You can also find beautiful clothes, cups and other souvenirs of M&M. The atmosphere is great. This is super fun shopping. I highly recommend to anyone who loves M&M.

M&M chocolates and it’s gems are like mouth watering. The ambience of this place is happening especially for kids and youth. Parents should visit this place at least once to enjoy M&m characters in every way. There are soft toys, show pieces, Different flag colours gems, cups memoirs. Love for this place. A huge colourful showroom with lot of interactive games, like finding the candy mood. Filling up your own jars with Chocolates of your colour. 💕💝

I had a sweet time in this tasty tasty store.  I was like a kid in a candy shop.   They have these awesome statues of the M&M characters, a huge number of souvieneers and a spot where you can customize your own M&MS and also on the second floor you can pick your own.  Be ready to spend money but you will have an awesome experience that will melt in your mouth not in your hands.
Amazing steel arch bridge.  There is a fantastic bike lane under the approach spans on Randals Island.
A masterpiece of architecture! Great place to explore and experience. Astoria park is a beautiful place.
An amazing and beautiful bridge to see from the triborough bridge.

Such an amazing view with the breeze from the river and view of Manhattan on the left side. 
The best view of the bridge is from Astoria Park. This bridge hold a train line, if you view the bridge from the Astoria Park other side of the river will be Randall island (which basically have a playground and couple of ship docking area) 

Behind the bridge you will see John F Kennedy bridge or Tri-borough bridge
Great place for a photo. Lest touristy then other NYC bridges. Best place to see the bridge is at the Randall's Island side

What a beautiful bridge!!! 
It's a pretty long walk but the beauty of the bridge keeps you going. Loved every minute spent walking on this bridge. And the view of the night city is amazing. The vibrant nature of the city is so contagious!!! :)

Fantastic engineering work. The bridge is beautiful. The view of Manhattan from the bridge is breathtaking. I recommend walking over the bridge. We visited it in the evening and we saw sunset. Wonderful. Very nice to see city in the lights with the  combination of sunset. It is always crowded on the bridge, but the experience is wonderful.

One of my favourite places to go for a relaxing walk and to take a couple of pictures. Great views of the city and Dumbo. Really beautiful sunsets during November and December. Don't stand/ walk in the bike lane unless you want to be run over.

One of my favourite places to go for a relaxing walk and to take a couple of pictures. Great views of the city and Dumbo. Really beautiful sunsets during November and December. Don't stand/ walk in the bike lane unless you want to be run over. Wind and Cold ... winter weather

One of the fun & free sightseeing in NYC, the view from the bridge is really beautiful and also after all the fatty food that this city have to offer it's nice to to a little walk to "burn" the fat. At the weekend it's a bit crowded but than you can earned a visit at Dumbo area at the Brooklyn side of the bridge. The metro is super close to the bridge on both sides (Manhattan & Brooklyn), on the Manhattan side it's worth to combine a visit on the bridge with wall street & world trade center area.

I had a great opportunity to attend the closing bell ceremony this year. It was exciting to see the rich history with this building. All over there were photos and artifacts from times past. I had the chance to see Betty Liu speak and they served guest light refreshments. It was near being in front of the anchor desk watching the all of the excitement just before the bell. Honestly, I zoomed in on the camera crew as that was pretty neat to see too. I hope I'm invited back one day!

This is a must see if you want to know how the economy works and a major force in the world. It really looks like chaos on the floor and the ringing of the bell still is something to be at. As a company listed on the NYSE, I was able to request a tour in advance of our last visit to NYC. There is so much history here that any businessman should go if they have a chance. If you can, be there for one of the bells.

Understanding the basics and what this building means to the entire world, literally rest yours and everybody else's basic everyday checking account on its shoulder. It deals with everybody money, and the world's money. Make sure you take a pic or two and just enjoy capitalism.

Got a chance to visit and the company I work for held a conference there so even had the privilege to walk around the NYSE for 2 days, the experience was amazing. 

Going through security was not fun, even though I walked in/out of that building maybe 5 times a day, they are still pretty strict about it. But after the 2nd day of walking in/out, some of the security guys remember me and let me through (so nice of them!). We also had a designated coordinator which we worked with throughout the entire event, so anything we needed or last minute request, she was able to pull through and helped us (super accommodating). 

Also got to visit the trading floor, definitely not what I thought it would be (assuming a scene from "Wolf of Wallstreet" didn't help either). There was no papers flying around or traders screaming at the top of their lungs and yelling at each other across the floor. It was very mellow and civilize and some were just on their phone drinking their coffee! 

It was such an honored to be able to tour around the NYSE and even able to worked there for a day. The venue is very grand, very clean and all the staff were super nice and friendly!

There is really a lot of cool things to see in this area. Some really cool pictures and beautiful architecture. You get to see where a lot of movies are made and get to touch the bull! They have some good eating places around. This will be about an hour experience to see it all. So you can plan this with other things in the area to do.

One of my favorite public spaces in the city.  There is always great people watching with a very diverse cross section of New Yorkers; from families to NYU students to artists and locals playing chess.  There are plenty of benches and places to sit and just enjoy the day.  And the mood, the park's atmosphere and attitude,  changes with the seasons,  absorbing the personality of the weather. Maybe you'll catch it one sweltering hot day and the fountain is on,  or you might end up sitting on a bench in autumn,  watching the leaves slowly drift down from the treetops.  Just beware the squirrels, they can't be trusted.

Take in the city like a local.  Manhattan is filled with hidden gems all over.  Washington Square Park is one of them.  Lay out a blanket and sit on the grass.  Watch one of the many live shows by locals.  Grab a pizza from nearby and enjoy people watching.  You can spend a half day there just enjoying the NYC vibe.

This place is beautiful and one of the NYC iconic landmarks bordering the East Village and Greenwich Village. Tons of restaurants, concert halls, theaters and cinemas in the area and an incredible vibe filled with NYU students and a mix of locals and tourists from all over the world. Options are endless, you can do yoga, meditate, lay on grass, walk your dog, play chess, listen to musicians play (literally on every corner), play some music and so much more. Great hangout spot.

Awesome park! I went in the winter and it was still bustling with plenty of people to watch. The lawns were closed but there was still ample seating in and around the fountain. The arch is awesome and is truly a sight to behold! I will be returning for sure.

This iconic park is almost always filed with vibrant people. It's a great place to go for a stroll and enjoy the fountain in the summer. In the winter time the fountain does not operate however people are always going inside where the fountain would be to take photos or just sit and relax. There's always something to see here and has great views

Beautiful park and world famous.  The park is absolutely massive and would recommend you take at least half a day to walk through just some of the many paths the park has on offer.  Amazingly calm place to be in the middle of all the hustle and bustle of America’s biggest city!!

Great and giant park. A place to walk and do excercises. Picnic and excellent pictures.. it's so good to see places from our favorite movies. Just use Google maps to know where you are. Just be careful It's easy to be lost in thousands of different roads. Great to see during winter summer spring or autumn. Any time of the year.

One of my top 10 things to do in New York city

My suggestion to everyone 
If you can start from Columbus Circle metro station. Nice views of Manhattan and central park. Grab some food from whole foods market and start to walk through central park. Bethesda fountain top 1 places to know!

Wonderful, huge park in the middle of Manhattan.  Even though it’s in the middle of one of the most densely populated areas in the U.S.A., you can still find quite areas of the park to relax. 

Very well maintained, there’s an abundance to do, from baseball parks, a zoo, in addition large open fields to peaceful walking paths.

Beautiful park year round! Great spot to explore as a tourist or run, walk, bike or bring your dog if you are a local! LOVE strawberry fields John Lennon’s memorial. 
Imagine all the people living life in peace. ☮️💟

Beautiful park, very well maintained. Everybody enjoying this wonderful green space in the middle of one of the most incredible cities in the world. For those whom enjoy running, this is a perfect place to add miles and free your mind from the troubles of the day.

Subsequent to my sons wedding, we went to the Boathouse for a small luncheon with our immediate family and my new and wonderful daughter-in-law and her family. It was a great experience. The company was fantastic, the appetizers were delicious, only to be outdone but the fabulous main course, and the desert was tremendous. The staff was excellent. They were very attentive to our needs and desires. Service was excellent!

Our group had a wonderful view of the lake from our table but it soon became a minor problem as the sun was shining through the window into the eyes of about half of the guests. It was requested that the exterior awnings be lowered to provide some shade to the affected guests but we were told that the awnings were in a fixed height position and could not be adjusted downward.

The inability to provide shade to our table is the only thing that is stopping me from giving 5 stars. I would gladly return to this facility but I would seek a shaded seating location or a room without a view. In all other aspects, our luncheon experience was superb.

This is a beautiful place with amazing food. We visited on a rainy day in the winter, but were seated by the windows. And even in the rain the views were beautiful! Our waiter was very helpful and friendly. Will definitely come back, hopefully in the summer when there are leaves on the trees and the windows are open!

One of my favorite ways to spend a sunny afternoon.  The key is to order at the counter (prices are MUCH more affordable vs getting table service inside) and bring your food/drink to the outside bar patio. The perfect spot to people watch and enjoy the juxtaposition of skyscrapers and nature.  We had the tuna on rye and an aperol spritz. (Spritz was a little weak but was worth the experience. )

Beautiful view of Central Park boating. Nice restaurant with white tablecloth. Arrive early and sit right in front of the pond. Service was great and waiters were friendly. If it’s a nice weekend day, expect a long wait. You clearly come for the view and the food was alright. Lunch menu can be limited — no salads and not many egg/omelette options.  I got the lox plate. They only have plain bagels and they aren’t the fresh kind from a nyc bagel spot. Tasted like a Thomas Plain bagel. If you are going to charge $28 at least have a decent bagel.

Beautiful restaurant in the middle of Central Park! Amazing food, and aesthetic. We ordered the crab cake which is unmatched! Must try if you go here. The hostess was rude when we entered and was dismissive. We called ahead of time to make a reservation. Also, noticed that the drinks were watered down, however the waiters were pleasant and kind. Ended up spending 350$ here, but slightly disappointed with the attitude of some of the staff.

An iconic global centre of the world that has inspired the world with its brilliant architecture, movies, and art. Also known as the Big Apple, New York is well-known for its magnificent skyscrapers, Broadway shows and beautiful landmarks, making it the perfect destination for travellers from all over the world. From the flashy neon lights and the hustle and bustle of Times Square to the skyscrapers of Wall Street and the verdant ways of Central Park, New York City never ceases to amaze with its energy and vibrancy. World-class exhibition halls like MoMA and exceptional world heritage sites like the Statue of Liberty are simply captivating. Broadway shows, ethnic enclaves and shops, memorable lanes of stately brownstones, in vogue bars and diners all add to the urban buzz. This modern city is home to millions of immigrants and is cosmopolitan in a way no other city can be.

This building is absolutely gorgeous and a true NYC landmark. However, if you're planning to go this month (FEB 2020), please know that there is scaffolding in front of it - so photos may not give the same lustre... Either way it's worth going to see it and then going over to Eataly, which is across the road!

This building is so beautiful and stays at the corner of 5th Ave with Broadway. It was the first skyscraper in NYC! You can only watch from outside but you have a beautiful garden at his left. You can lunch and watch squirrels trying to steal food from people.

Going on the Statue of Liberty tour is a good, cheap activity to do with your family/friends. As one of the seven Wonders of the World, it's a great experience to see at least once! Navigating throughout the website to buy the tickets was pretty easy, and we just ended up getting the most basic tickets - ground level. To order the tickets to go on higher levels/inside the Statue of Liberty, you will definitely have to order at least 4-6 months ahead of time.
Very cool iconic building in NYC, did not go inside or anything but the architecture outside is worthy enough to pay this place a visit.

It is a very nice museum. It’s not so big that you feel like you need to rush but not so small that you’re bored, you can go at a very leisurely pace which is nice. The library is absolutely incredible and is where you have to go. There are so many books and it’s just wild to see what he collected. Nice place to go to and walk around in the middle of the day and then eat at their restaurant in the afternoon. Would recommend going here.

This place is breathtaking. Simple as that. The entrance to the library is free, but the exhibitions have an admittance fee. No matter. They have created a marvelous hub of art, literature and knowledge. And never, ever in my life I would have dreamt that on one rainy day in Manhattan I would come to lay my eyes on a Gutenberg bible. I cannot stress enough how truly exceptional this is. Go. See it. Sit down in that glorious room and just take it all in.

I went to see the John Singer Sargent exhibit. The show was well displayed. The museum is a very nice small gallery in the heart of mid town.
Excellent bar and cafe inside the museum. I would recommend this gallery for the quality and ease.

For a museum, this is small.  For a home, it is spectacular. The high light is the library but all of the architecture is marvelous.  The museum displays are typically modest but of high-quality. My only quibble is with the cost of admission - but all museums have become pricey. I would not make this a must-see site on your first visit to New York unless you have a specific interest in Morgan.  Nonetheless, it is well worth seeing (and just a short walk from the Empire State Building in case you wish to combine the sites for a day outing.)

The private library was quite impressive.  See a real Gutenberg Bible, impressive even to an atheist. The docent tour was a great introduction.  We were lucky enough to see the John Singer Sargent show, but there are always several, likely high quality exhibits.  The cafe looked good and the fine dining room, with a priced fixed menu (only open for lunch) looked delicious and like a good place to celebrate and indulge.

Beautiful mall right on Columbus Circle with several high end shops catering to the more sophisticated shoppers.  The impressive lobby has hanging stars that changes lights every second. Be sure to check out the third floor for some good food.

Looking for a place to go shopping with tons of stores and great dining around the Columbus Circle area?  Then stop by the Time Warner Center.  They have everything from grocery shopping at WholeFoods to getting some running shoes to Amazon Go to bakeries!  All things in one!

I love this Center. Great variety of high end shops and eateries all contribute to an excellent atmosphere. Great view from the balcony out of the giant glass windows onto Columbus Circle and a slice of Central Park. Two giant male and female, modern art sculptures, stand either side of the escalators, welcoming visitors. It is a tradition to touch them as you pass. The result is very shiny. Neither seem to mind.
Lots of shopping options. High end retail stores. Bathrooms. Amazon book store. A few sit down dining choices. Some ultra high end dinner restaurants. Whole Foods is downstairs.

One of my favourite places to visit when in Nyc. A part from the chouce of great restaurants, I like to spend time watching Lincoln Circle and the corner of Central Park 'framed' through the glass windows of the Time Warner Center. From the second level the view is spectacular.

This a great family friendly venue. I encourage anyone from all walks of life to enjoy the day here. Children of all ages have a great time and learn. It’s an overall empowering experience. Even parents have a good time. The skyscrapers exhibit is amazing and interactive. The newly renovated planetarium is awesome. In warmer weather they open up outdoor exhibits. All in all great experience and never have to worry about weather concerns.

Geared towards younger children maybe 5-12 would get the best total experience. 
Having said that we brought our 3 year old grandson and although some things were a little above his level there was plenty of things to keep him engaged. He had a great time as did we.
The planetarium was showing a Big Bird narrated lesson on the stars and at my age I was able to enjoy the show along with my grandson.  
The planetarium is definitely a must do if you visit here.
Every one of the staff that we interacted with was extremely professional and super helpful. 
You could definitely tell they were as happy to be there as we were. 
Parking is plentiful and its a 3 minute walk from the light rail. 
All in all a great day.

The Liberty Science Center is one of the most ridiculously underrated places I've been to during my time on the east coast. While this might very much seem like a place that you'd organize day trips for toddlers, I took a leap of faith and organized a birthday surprise for my partner that started from this place and we ended up having a wonderful time.

The tickets on entry might seem a tad too expensive (~40 something) but believe me that it's completely worth it. The place is divided into multiple floors so lets start from the top. There is an aquarium on the last floor and it's remarkable how well it has been maintained. I was thoroughly impressed to see an aquarium of such scale to be located within a science centre. The other floors are filled with interesting technical exhibits and if you're a geek at heart then you're surely going to love it every bit.

I'd highly highly recommend paying a visit to the Dome Theatre [irrespective of the show that's currently playing]. The audio visual experience is absolutely stunning and given the smart duration of a show [~45 minutes], it's unlikely that you'll be bored.

Also, there's a cute little cafe which serves pizzas and other essentials and a wonderful gift shop on the ground floor that deserves a stop-over as well.

Certainly a place to cherish and visit once in a while for folks belonging to all ages.

We had really high expectations and were greatly disappointed. Very few interesting parts. For the interesting ones you have to pay extra. The exhibitions seems mainly be targeted at really small children... If you like to see a really good science museum you could visit the German museum in Munich.

The museum ticket is very expensive in my opinion but the Liberty Science Center is very cool and good museum. There are many exhibits that you can see. I was surprised there was an aquarium in a science center. I think that's the first time in my life I experience that. There are also some film showings that some people can enjoy. This is a perfect place to take kids.

A beautiful park with beautiful views of some of the most iconic buildings in New York. From the park you can see the Empire State Building and the Flatiron Building. The park is pet friendly 🐈 🐕 with areas designated for pets to play. There's a burger joint with one of the most amazing burgers I've ever had. It's relatively small so if you want a huge space to run or play with your pets then I suggest another park. There are numerous public benches where you can sit and relax. 
🐱🐕‍🦺🦮🐩🦽🦼

One of my favorite places in the city. Come summer you have to enjoy all of the performers and people enjoying the green space. It's lovely and has a dog park and chess tables. Nice restaurants nearby and a minor escape from the hustle and bustle of NYC living.

This is a beautiful park with the added bonus of having a Shake Shack so that you can rest and find a tasty snack all in one place. We like to walk our dog here where we meet lots of other small dog owners. It's a nice alternative to dog runs. People you meet may not remember your name but your dog's name will be remembered.

This is literally my favorite area in NYC. There is so much going on that you can come here everyday and see a new store. The park is GORGEOUS and always well kept. There's food inside and outside of the park. I love going to Eatly across the street, getting food, and having a picnic at the park! The fountains are so pretty and the flowers are colorful and beautiful as well. I always stop here on my trips to NYC. Definitely a must see!
Love this place during the summer. When all the fields are open.. feel more safe to watch my 2 kids when you have closed space.. can't wait for the fields to open in May
